Upon examining the histograms from both the horeca and retail channels, we made several observations:¶

  • Despite Horeca customers making up nearly 68% of the total, their average annual spending across all categories is only 26,844 while Retail customers account for 46619
  • Retail customers spend more on Milk, Groceries, and Detergents_paper than Horeca customers.
  • Both channels see similar overall spending patterns for the rest of the categories, despite Horeca customers slightly spend more on food-related categories such as: Fresh produce and Frozen products.

Task 3: Data Modelling¶

In this Task, We're going to use K-Nearest Neighbours (KNN) and DecisionTree classification model to make a prediction for 'Channel' feature.

3.1 Splitting the dataset¶

In [71]:
# Split data into features and target
X = df.drop('Channel', axis=1)
y = df['Channel']
In [72]:
# Split data into training and testing sets with different ratios:
# Suite1: 50% for training and 50% for testing:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
X1_train, X1_test, y1_train, y1_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.5, random_state=1)

# Suite2: 60% for training and 40% for testing:
X2_train, X2_test, y2_train, y2_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.4, random_state=2)

# Suite3: 80% for training and 20% for testing:
X3_train, X3_test, y3_train, y3_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.2, random_state=3)

3.2 and 3.3 Applying Classification models on these 3 suites and Comparing the two chosen models¶

Applying on Suite1¶

KNN model¶

In [88]:
# Firstly, we're use cross-validation method to find the right K for Suite1
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier

neighbors = list(range(1, 50, 2))
cv_scores = []

# Perform 10-fold cross-validation
for k in neighbors:
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k)
    scores = cross_val_score(knn, X1_train, y1_train, cv=10, scoring='accuracy')
    cv_scores.append(scores.mean())

# Find the optimal value of K that maximizes accuracy
optimal_k = neighbors[cv_scores.index(max(cv_scores))]

print("Optimal value of K:", optimal_k)

Optimal value of K: 15
In [89]:
knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=15)
knn_trained = knn.fit(X1_train, y1_train)
y1_pred = knn_trained.predict(X1_test)
In [93]:
# Evaluating the performances of the model on Suite1 in terms of Confusion matrix, Classification accuracy, 
# Precision, Recall and F1 score:
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score

# Calculate and print metrics
con_knn1 = confusion_matrix(y1_test, y1_pred)
acc_knn1 = accuracy_score(y1_test, y1_pred)
prec_knn1 = precision_score(y1_test, y1_pred, average='weighted')
recall_knn1 = recall_score(y1_test, y1_pred, average='weighted')
f1_knn1 = f1_score(y1_test, y1_pred, average='weighted')
metrics_knn1 = [acc_knn1, prec_knn1, recall_knn1, f1_knn1]
print("Confusion Matrix KNN 1:\n", con_knn1)
print(metrics_knn1)

    for j in range(2):
        axs[0].text(j, i, con_knn1[i, j], ha='center', va='center', color='red')
